Architecture plan

Scope
- Issues #23-#32 finish the existing statically exported Next.js App Router marketing site for ZeroClaw / "Agent Team for Founders".
- The current foundation already includes the root shell, shared layout components, UI primitives, hero section, value proposition section, Tailwind, static export scripts, and public CTA environment wiring.
- This batch should add the remaining homepage sections, compose the final route, configure social/search metadata assets, then verify responsive, accessibility, E2E, export, and plain static serving behavior.

Module structure and file organization
- Keep the repository root as the Next.js application root.
- App shell:
  - `app/layout.tsx` owns `html`/`body`, font loading, global metadata, skip link, and shared `Header`/`Footer`.
  - `app/page.tsx` should remain the explicit homepage composition point. Final order: `Hero`, `ValueProposition`, `HowItWorks`, `FeaturesBenefits`, and `CallToAction`.
  - `app/globals.css` holds Tailwind directives, design tokens, base styles, accessibility helpers, and any final responsive polish that belongs globally.
- Section components:
  - Existing: `components/sections/hero.tsx`, `components/sections/value-proposition.tsx`.
  - Add: `components/sections/how-it-works.tsx`, `components/sections/features-benefits.tsx`, `components/sections/call-to-action.tsx`.
  - Each section should expose one named React component and own its narrow copy/data arrays unless the data is shared elsewhere.
- Shared primitives and layout:
  - Reuse `components/ui/button.tsx`, `components/ui/card.tsx`, `components/ui/icon.tsx`, `components/ui/section.tsx`, and `components/layout/content-container.tsx`.
  - Avoid new component abstractions unless two or more sections need the same behavior or markup contract.
- Shared configuration and types:
  - `lib/env.ts` remains the single source for public CTA URL/default handling.
  - `lib/navigation.ts` remains the source for anchor IDs and nav labels used by header/footer/sections.
  - Keep data item types colocated with each section, such as `HowItWorksStep` or `FeatureBenefit`, unless multiple modules need them.
- Static assets:
  - Favicon and OG assets belong under `public/`, preferably `public/favicon.ico`, `public/icon.svg` or PNG variants, and `public/images/og-image.png`.
  - `robots.txt` and `sitemap.xml` belong directly in `public/` for static export.
- Tests and verification:
  - Add Playwright configuration/tests only when issue #31 is implemented, likely under `tests/e2e/` or `e2e/` using the repo's existing conventions at that time.
  - Static export verification for #32 should exercise `npm run build` and `npm run serve` against `out/`.

Dependencies between issues
- #23 and #24 both depend on the existing shared UI primitives and design tokens. They can be implemented independently after the current `Hero` and `ValueProposition` sections.
- #25 depends on the public CTA URL handling in `lib/env.ts` and should reuse the same button/link pattern as the hero CTA.
- #26 depends on #23, #24, #25, plus the existing hero and value proposition sections. It should only compose sections and ensure anchor targets line up with navigation.
- #27 depends on the brand/content direction already present in the hero/value proposition copy. It can precede #28 but should reference stable asset paths that #28 will add.
- #28 depends on #27's metadata decisions or should update metadata if asset names differ.
- #29 depends on static export configuration and the final canonical site URL decision. Keep it simple and static unless a dynamic sitemap generator is later required.
- #30 depends on all visual sections being present. Fix responsive, semantic, focus, contrast, and reduced-motion issues before locking in E2E expectations.
- #31 depends on #26 and should ideally run after #30 so tests assert the final accessible layout rather than temporary markup.
- #32 depends on #31 and static export configuration. It is the final release gate for the plain-directory deployment model.

Key design decisions
- Stay fully static: do not introduce server actions, route handlers, runtime secrets, or dynamic rendering behavior that would conflict with `output: "export"`.
- Keep the homepage as a small set of typed, data-driven sections. Copy arrays can live beside each section for readability and easy issue-by-issue review.
- Use established primitives before creating new styling patterns. Cards should remain for repeated items; broader page bands should be section layouts, not nested card surfaces.
- Navigation and section IDs must be centralized so header, footer, sitemap, smoke tests, and sections do not drift.
- CTA links should always come from public env configuration with a safe default, and should use accessible link text rather than icon-only affordances.
- Metadata should use Next.js `Metadata` in `app/layout.tsx`, with explicit Open Graph and Twitter card fields and public image paths compatible with static hosting.
- Robots and sitemap should assume the canonical production URL chosen by the project. If no production domain is available when #29 lands, document the fallback and keep replacement localized.
- Responsive and accessibility review should prioritize keyboard navigation, visible focus states, heading order, landmark structure, contrast, mobile menu behavior, and section spacing at mobile/tablet/desktop widths.
- E2E coverage should stay narrow: page loads, expected sections render, navigation anchors work, and the primary CTA resolves to the configured target.
- Final export validation should serve `out/` with the repo's `serve` script and verify the rendered page, static assets, metadata files, robots, and sitemap are reachable without a Next.js server.
